#Use Network security policies to restrict cluster level access

Network policies controlam o trafico entre pods no kubernetes. Definindo esseas policies, você pode limitar qual pod pode comunicar com outro ou servicos externos.
Exemplo:
```
## Network policy
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-specific-namespace
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      role: backend
  policyTypes:
  - Ingress
  - Egress
  ingress:
  - from:
    - namespaceSelector:
        matchLabels:
          kubernetes.io/metadata.name: trusted
  egress:
  - {}
```

Nessa network police os pods com labels, role: backend só poderam aceitar trafego de entrada dos pods da namespace: trusted

O arquivo 1-exemple.yaml tem um conjunto de objetos que vamos utilizar para entender melhor essa comunicação.
```
$ k apply -f 1-example.yaml
```

Para validar a comunicação interna do pod backend:
```
$ k exec -it backend -- curl 127.0.0.1
```

Resultado esperado: 
```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Welcome to nginx!</title>
<style>
html { color-scheme: light dark; }
body { width: 35em; margin: 0 auto;
font-family: Tahoma, Verdana, Arial, sans-serif; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Welcome to nginx!</h1>
<p>If you see this page, the nginx web server is successfully installed and
working. Further configuration is required.</p>

<p>For online documentation and support please refer to
<a href="http://nginx.org/">nginx.org</a>.<br/>
Commercial support is available at
<a href="http://nginx.com/">nginx.com</a>.</p>

<p><em>Thank you for using nginx.</em></p>
</body>
</html>
```

Agora vamos testar do pod untrusted:

Vamos pegar o fqdn do pod backend
```
$ k get po -o wide
```

FQDN é composto do ip do pod separado por -, seguido do namespace, .pod e o nome do cluster. No meu caso:
```
10-233-119-32.default.pod.cluster.local
```

Validando a conexão: 
```
$ k exec -it -n untrusted untrusted -- curl 10-233-119-32.default.pod.cluster.local
```

Resultado esperado: 
```
curl: (28) Failed to connect to 10-233-119-32.default.pod.cluster.local port 80 after 132741 ms: Could not connect to server
command terminated with exit code 28
```

Agora testando do pod trusted: 
```
$ k exec -it -n trusted trusted -- curl 10-233-119-32.default.pod.cluster.local
```
Resultado esperado: 
```
k exec -it -n trusted trusted -- curl 10-233-119-32.default.pod.cluster.local
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Welcome to nginx!</title>
<style>
html { color-scheme: light dark; }
body { width: 35em; margin: 0 auto;
font-family: Tahoma, Verdana, Arial, sans-serif; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Welcome to nginx!</h1>
<p>If you see this page, the nginx web server is successfully installed and
working. Further configuration is required.</p>

<p>For online documentation and support please refer to
<a href="http://nginx.org/">nginx.org</a>.<br/>
Commercial support is available at
<a href="http://nginx.com/">nginx.com</a>.</p>

<p><em>Thank you for using nginx.</em></p>
</body>
</html>
```



